<font color="#FF0000">TO ROY C.</font><br>
<tt>Thu Jan  1 23:24:30 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
Roy<br><br>
Your insights are interesting and your background reveals your commitment and experiences on both sides of the border. Welcome home Bro.<br><br>
When I returned home and put on a badge I became aware that those protesting the war were far from seeking the peace they proclaimed. Their leaders motives were far from seeking to stop a war in South East Asia. <br><br>
The hypocrisy you speak about I saw then and have seen in the postings by others here. I cannot image being involved in an anti-war movement for eight years and not having participated in the drugs, sex or the violence I saw as a young police officer. Yes, I did arrest and bash in heads on the streets of Los Angeles in the early 70’s. I also recovered a whole lot of communist propaganda from their person and from their headquarters. Many of those arrest reports can be viewed today under the freedom of information act and they would fill in a lot of holes. <br><br>
We seemed to have forgotten the anti-war mistress of  those days, a lot still needs to be revealed before real healing to our nation can occur, before American can look inward and see that it wasn’t just selfish  government officials that caused the pain, and sorrow and the war in Vietnam, but a well set up communist conspiracy within our own borders. A lot has been declassified and many books can be and have yet to be written.  Those I arrested then were hard core communist sympathizers, left wing radicals full of hate toward our government, the U.S. military and corporate America.<br><br>
I am looking forward to meaningful dialog on this subject. We can learn a lot from each other, and I welcome your contribution.<br>
I agree with your summarization, <br><br>
“I don't need your 'I told you so's.'Let's heal as a nation.”<br><br>
It reminds me very much of Rodney King’s declaration as the city burned behind him, <br><br>
“Can’t we all get along.”<br><br>
Cook<br><br>

